---
title: Mild Sri Lankan Fish Curry with Green Beans and Cardamom Rice
description: This dish is inspired by Mimi’s time in Asia. The curries we get in the UK are often thick and very rich, but this little number is delicate and fresh. We’re hoping it will transport your taste buds to the Sri Lankan coast! Traditional Sri Lankan fish dishes often involve marinating for several hours but we’ve used some HelloFresh magic to whip this one up in just half an hour, using a delicious Seasoned Pioneers spice - enjoy!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/mimi-s-coastal-fish-curry-37-c0bb653f-6acbbdac.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/mimi-s-coastal-fish-curry-37-578f5a2ad804b5914f8b456a-ffed1de9.pdf
course: main course
time required: 30 minutes
author: Mimi Morley
nutrition:
  calories: 615 kcal
  fat: 21 g
  saturated fat: 17 g
  carbohydrates: 73 g
  sugar: 8 g
  protein: 32 g
  sodium: 1 g
  serving size: 487
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/mimi-s-coastal-fish-curry-37-578f5a2ad804b5914f8b456a
cuisine: Asian
servings: 2
---

Zest and juice the @lime{1}. Pour half the lime juice into a #mixing bowl{} and set the zest aside for later. Cut each @coley fillet{2} into four pieces and add to the bowl with the juice. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @pepper{pinch}. Set aside to marinate.

Pour the @water{300} into a large #saucepan{} with half the @vegetable stock powder{1} and the @cardamom pod{1}. Bring to the boil, stir to dissolve the stock pot and add the @basmati rice{150}. Bring back to the boil and cover with a #lid{}. Cook on medium-low heat for ~{10%minutes}, then remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes}.

> TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into roughly 1cm pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim the tops from the @green beans{150} and chop them into thirds.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the @mustard seeds{1}. Once they begin to pop, add the onion and lime zest. Cook on low heat until the onion is soft, ~{5%minutes}, then add the @Sri Lankan curry powder{1} and garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute} more.

> TIP: If you leave the mustard seeds for too long on their own they'll start jumping out of the pan, so make sure you keep an eye on them!

Pour the @water{50} and @coconut milk{200} into the frying pan. Add the remaining stock pot and the green beans. Stir everything together. Simmer gently for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Carefully add the fish along with any lime juice left in the bowl. Gently submerge it in the sauce but be careful not to break the pieces up. Cover with a lid (or some #foil{}) and poach the fish on low heat, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove the cardamom pods from the rice and fluff it up with a #fork{}. Serve your delicious fish curry atop a generous heap of rice. Cut the remaining lime into wedges and serve on the side. Enjoy!